{"cursor":"14900","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"An 'incentive' is something that motivates an individual to perform an\naction. The study of incentive structures is central to the study of all\neconomic activity (both in terms of individual decision-making and in terms\nof co-operation and competition within a larger institutional structure).\nEconomic analysis, then, of the differences between societies (and between\ndifferent organizations within a society) largely amounts to characterizing\nthe differences in 'incentive structures' faced by individuals involved in\nthese collective efforts. Ultimately, incentives aim to provide value for\nmoney and contribute to organizational success. {{cite book\n| last = Armstrong first = Michael title = Employee Reward publisher = CIPD\n| House''' | year = 2002\n}}\n","linknr":154,"url":"incentives","recorded":1364192371,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Incentive&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Incentive&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Incentive","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Incentives&redirect=no","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Co-operation","/wiki/Competition","#cite_note-Organisational_Success-1","#Categories","#Other_forms","#Social_pressure","#Ec